---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Nav from "../components/Nav.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
---

<Layout title="Quantroot — Understanding SPHINCS+ Signatures">
  <Nav />
  <main class="pt-32 pb-20">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6">

      <h1 class="mb-4 text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight">Understanding SPHINCS+</h1>
      <p class="mb-12 text-lg text-text-secondary">
        A visual walkthrough of how hash-based post-quantum signatures work
        and why Quantroot uses them to protect Bitcoin.
      </p>

      <!-- Section 1: What is SPHINCS+ -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-bold">What is SPHINCS+?</h2>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          SPHINCS+ (standardized as SLH-DSA in NIST FIPS 205) is a post-quantum
          digital signature scheme. It replaces the elliptic-curve math behind
          ECDSA and Schnorr with nothing but <strong class="text-text-primary">hash
          functions</strong> &mdash; the same primitives you already know from
          <code class="text-text-primary">SHA-256</code> and block explorers.
          That substitution is what makes it safe against quantum computers.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          At the highest level, SPHINCS+ is built from a handful of
          cryptographic pieces stacked on top of each other. You will see these
          names repeatedly:
        </p>

        <div class="overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-border bg-surface-raised">
          <table class="w-full text-sm">
            <tbody>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="p-4 font-mono font-semibold text-quantum align-top w-32">WOTS+</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-text-secondary">One-time signature made from hash chains. Signs a single message.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="p-4 font-mono font-semibold text-quantum align-top">Merkle tree</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-text-secondary">Binary tree of hashes that commits to many values under one root.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="p-4 font-mono font-semibold text-quantum align-top">XMSS</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-text-secondary">A Merkle tree of WOTS+ keys &mdash; multi-time signing, but <em>stateful</em>.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="p-4 font-mono font-semibold text-quantum align-top">FORS</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-text-secondary">A "few-time" signature over a forest of small Merkle trees. Signs the message hash.</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="p-4 font-mono font-semibold text-quantum align-top">Hypertree</td>
                <td class="p-4 text-text-secondary">A tree of XMSS trees that lets one small public key authenticate billions of signatures.</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 2: What is a Digital Signature? -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-bold">What is a Digital Signature?</h2>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          Before getting into SPHINCS+, it's worth being precise about what a
          signature scheme actually <em>does</em>. A digital signature is a
          piece of math that proves three things at once:
        </p>

        <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3 mb-8">
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-surface-raised p-5">
            <div class="mb-3 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-quantum">Who</div>
            <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
              Only the holder of a specific private key could have produced
              this signature.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-surface-raised p-5">
            <div class="mb-3 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-quantum">What</div>
            <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
              The signature is tied to one exact message. Change a single byte
              and the signature no longer matches.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-surface-raised p-5">
            <div class="mb-3 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-quantum">Verifiable</div>
            <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
              Anyone can check it using only the public key &mdash; no
              interaction with the signer required.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          Think of it as a <strong class="text-text-primary">wax seal made of
          math</strong>. Only the person with the signet ring (the private key)
          can stamp it, and anyone with a picture of the seal (the public key)
          can tell whether a document was stamped by the real ring or a forgery.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          In Bitcoin, signatures are how the network decides whether to believe
          a transaction. When you spend a UTXO, your wallet produces a
          signature over the transaction data, and every node on the planet
          independently verifies it. If the signature is valid, the coins move.
          If it isn't, the transaction is rejected.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          If the math underneath a signature scheme breaks, an attacker can
          produce valid-looking signatures for transactions you never
          authorized. Bitcoin addresses are <em>hashes</em> of public keys, so
          funds at a never-used address are safe even if ECDSA breaks &mdash;
          but the moment you spend from an address, its public key is revealed
          on-chain, and any change that went back to the same address is
          suddenly at risk. Post-quantum signatures exist to make sure that
          window of vulnerability never opens.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3: What is a Hash Function? -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-bold">What is a Hash Function?</h2>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          SPHINCS+ is built almost entirely out of hash functions, so it's
          worth a minute to define what one is. A
          <strong class="text-text-primary">hash function</strong> is a kind of
          one-way blender for data. You feed in any input &mdash; a word, a
          file, a whole book, a Bitcoin transaction &mdash; and you get back a
          fixed-size fingerprint of that input, typically 256 bits (32 bytes).
          The hash function Bitcoin uses internally is called
          <strong class="text-text-primary">SHA-256</strong>.
        </p>

        <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3 mb-8">
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-surface-raised p-5">
            <div class="mb-3 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-quantum">Fast one-way</div>
            <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
              Computing <code class="text-text-primary">H(x)</code> from
              <code class="text-text-primary">x</code> takes microseconds.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-surface-raised p-5">
            <div class="mb-3 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-quantum">Impossible to reverse</div>
            <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
              Given a fingerprint, there is no known way to recover the input
              &mdash; finding one would take longer than the age of the
              universe.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-surface-raised p-5">
            <div class="mb-3 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-quantum">Tiny changes ripple out</div>
            <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
              Flipping a single bit of the input produces a completely
              different-looking fingerprint. There is no way to nudge a hash.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          That's the whole toolkit SPHINCS+ is built from. No modular
          arithmetic, no elliptic curves, no secret algebra &mdash; just a
          one-way blender applied over and over again in clever patterns. The
          rest of this guide is really just <em>here are the clever patterns</em>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4: Why Hash-Based? -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-bold">Why Hash-Based Signatures?</h2>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          Every signature scheme rests on some math problem that is hard to
          reverse. For Bitcoin's current signatures &mdash; ECDSA and Schnorr &mdash;
          that problem is the <strong class="text-text-primary">Elliptic Curve
          Discrete Logarithm Problem</strong> (ECDLP).
        </p>

        <div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 mb-8">
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-btc-orange/30 bg-surface-raised p-6">
            <div class="mb-3 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-btc-orange">ECDSA / Schnorr</div>
            <div class="mb-3 font-mono text-sm text-text-secondary">
              <div>private: <span class="text-text-primary">d</span></div>
              <div>public:&nbsp; <span class="text-text-primary">P = d·G</span></div>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-text-secondary">
              Forward direction is easy: multiply the generator <code class="text-text-primary">G</code>
              by <code class="text-text-primary">d</code>. The reverse &mdash;
              recover <code class="text-text-primary">d</code> from
              <code class="text-text-primary">P</code> &mdash; takes ≈2<sup>128</sup>
              operations classically.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-quantum/30 bg-surface-raised p-6">
            <div class="mb-3 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-quantum">SPHINCS+</div>
            <div class="mb-3 font-mono text-sm text-text-secondary">
              <div>private: <span class="text-text-primary">s</span></div>
              <div>public:&nbsp; <span class="text-text-primary">H(H(...H(s)))</span></div>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-text-secondary">
              Forward direction is easy: hash the secret many times. The
              reverse &mdash; invert <code class="text-text-primary">H</code> &mdash;
              is infeasible both classically <em>and</em> on a quantum computer.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          To put 2<sup>128</sup> in perspective: if every computer on Earth
          today worked on cracking a single key, the sun would burn out first.
          This is the "hard problem" Bitcoin's current signatures depend on.
        </p>

        <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold">The quantum problem</h3>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          In 1994 Peter Shor published an algorithm that, when run on a
          quantum computer, solves the discrete-log problem in
          <strong class="text-text-primary">polynomial time</strong> &mdash;
          roughly, "fast enough to matter in practice." A sufficiently large
          quantum computer running Shor's algorithm could recover the private
          key <code class="text-text-primary">d</code> from the public key
          <code class="text-text-primary">P</code> in hours instead of the
          effectively infinite 2<sup>128</sup> operations classically. This
          doesn't just break ECDSA &mdash; it breaks everything in the same
          family: Schnorr, RSA, Diffie-Hellman.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          Nobody has built such a machine yet. Current quantum computers are
          far too small and noisy to run Shor's on a 256-bit key. But
          cryptographic standards are slow to change, and coins that are safe
          today need to stay safe in a decade. That's why the work is
          happening now.
        </p>

        <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold">Why hashing survives</h3>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          Hash functions don't rely on the kind of algebraic structure Shor's
          algorithm exploits. The best known quantum attack against a hash
          function is <strong class="text-text-primary">Grover's algorithm</strong>
          &mdash; a general-purpose quantum speedup for brute-force search
          &mdash; which only speeds things up by a <em>quadratic</em> factor:
          2<sup>n</sup> becomes 2<sup>n/2</sup>. Simply use a larger hash
          output and you're back where you started. A 256-bit hash still
          provides 128-bit security against a quantum attacker, the same
          level Bitcoin's Schnorr already targets.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 3: WOTS+ -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-bold">Building Block 1: WOTS+ (Hash Chains)</h2>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          The Winternitz One-Time Signature (WOTS+) scheme is the first real
          hash-based signature we'll meet. It starts from an idea you have
          probably already seen in Bitcoin: a
          <strong class="text-text-primary">hash commitment</strong>.
        </p>

        <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold">Starting point: hash commitments</h3>
        <p class="mb-4 text-text-secondary">
          To prove later that you knew a secret <code class="text-text-primary">s</code>,
          publish <code class="text-text-primary">H(s)</code> today. When you
          eventually reveal <code class="text-text-primary">s</code>, anyone can
          compute the hash and check it against the commitment. Nobody can forge
          this because inverting <code class="text-text-primary">H</code> is
          infeasible.
        </p>

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-surface-raised p-6 font-mono text-sm mb-6">
          <div class="text-text-secondary">commit → <span class="text-quantum">H(s)</span> &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="text-text-secondary/60">(published today, keeps s secret)</span></div>
          <div class="text-text-secondary">reveal → <span class="text-text-primary">s</span> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="text-text-secondary/60">(published later)</span></div>
          <div class="text-text-secondary">verify → H(s) == commit ?</div>
        </div>

        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          Lightning Network invoices work exactly this way. The receiver picks a
          random preimage <code class="text-text-primary">s</code>, hashes it,
          and puts <code class="text-text-primary">H(s)</code> &mdash; the
          <em>payment hash</em> &mdash; into the invoice. A payment is routed
          with the condition "release funds only against a preimage that hashes
          to <code class="text-text-primary">H(s)</code>." When the receiver
          reveals <code class="text-text-primary">s</code>, routing nodes verify
          the hash and forward the settlement. No signature, no key exchange &mdash;
          just a hash.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          A single commitment like this isn't yet a digital signature: it only
          proves knowledge of one pre-agreed secret, once. WOTS+ takes the same
          primitive and stretches it into something much more powerful by
          chaining many hashes together and using the <em>position</em> in the
          chain to encode a message.
        </p>

        <h3 class="mb-3 text-lg font-semibold">The hash chain</h3>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          Pick a random secret <code class="text-text-primary">s</code>. Apply
          the hash function <code class="text-text-primary">H</code> to it
          <code class="text-text-primary">w</code> times in a row. The end of
          the chain is the public key. To sign a digit
          <code class="text-text-primary">d</code>, reveal the intermediate hash
          <code class="text-text-primary">H<sup>d</sup>(s)</code>. A verifier
          can hash the rest of the way to the public key.
        </p>

        <!-- Animated hash chain -->
        <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-surface-raised p-6 overflow-hidden mb-4">
          <div class="mb-4 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-text-secondary">
            Interactive: Click a position to "sign" that value
          </div>
          <div class="hash-chain flex items-center justify-between gap-1 overflow-x-auto py-4" id="hashChain">
            <div class="chain-node secret shrink-0 flex flex-col items-center gap-1 cursor-pointer" data-index="0">
              <div class="h-10 w-10 rounded-lg bg-quantum/20 border border-quantum/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-mono text-quantum transition-all">s</div>
              <span class="text-[10px] text-text-secondary">secret</span>
            </div>
            <div class="shrink-0 text-text-secondary/30">→</div>
            <div class="chain-node shrink-0 flex flex-col items-center gap-1 cursor-pointer" data-index="1">
              <div class="h-10 w-10 rounded-lg bg-surface-overlay border border-border flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-mono text-text-secondary transition-all">H¹</div>
              <span class="text-[10px] text-text-secondary">1</span>
            </div>
            <div class="shrink-0 text-text-secondary/30">→</div>
            <div class="chain-node shrink-0 flex flex-col items-center gap-1 cursor-pointer" data-index="2">
              <div class="h-10 w-10 rounded-lg bg-surface-overlay border border-border flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-mono text-text-secondary transition-all">H²</div>
              <span class="text-[10px] text-text-secondary">2</span>
            </div>
            <div class="shrink-0 text-text-secondary/30">→</div>
            <div class="chain-node shrink-0 flex flex-col items-center gap-1 cursor-pointer" data-index="3">
              <div class="h-10 w-10 rounded-lg bg-surface-overlay border border-border flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-mono text-text-secondary transition-all">H³</div>
              <span class="text-[10px] text-text-secondary">3</span>
            </div>
            <div class="shrink-0 text-text-secondary/30">→</div>
            <div class="chain-node shrink-0 flex flex-col items-center gap-1 cursor-pointer" data-index="4">
              <div class="h-10 w-10 rounded-lg bg-surface-overlay border border-border flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-mono text-text-secondary transition-all">H⁴</div>
              <span class="text-[10px] text-text-secondary">4</span>
            </div>
            <div class="shrink-0 text-text-secondary/30">→</div>
            <div class="chain-node shrink-0 flex flex-col items-center gap-1 cursor-pointer" data-index="5">
              <div class="h-10 w-10 rounded-lg bg-surface-overlay border border-border flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-mono text-text-secondary transition-all">H⁵</div>
              <span class="text-[10px] text-text-secondary">5</span>
            </div>
            <div class="shrink-0 text-text-secondary/30">→</div>
            <div class="chain-node shrink-0 flex flex-col items-center gap-1 cursor-pointer" data-index="6">
              <div class="h-10 w-10 rounded-lg bg-surface-overlay border border-border flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-mono text-text-secondary transition-all">H⁶</div>
              <span class="text-[10px] text-text-secondary">6</span>
            </div>
            <div class="shrink-0 text-text-secondary/30">→</div>
            <div class="chain-node pubkey shrink-0 flex flex-col items-center gap-1">
              <div class="h-10 w-10 rounded-lg bg-btc-orange/20 border border-btc-orange/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs font-mono text-btc-orange">pk</div>
              <span class="text-[10px] text-text-secondary">public</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div id="chainStatus" class="text-center text-sm text-text-secondary mt-2">
            Click any position to see how signing works
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          The security of the scheme comes from hash-function asymmetry. Given
          <code class="text-text-primary">H<sup>5</sup>(s)</code>, the verifier
          can trivially hash <em>forward</em> to the public key. But a forger
          trying to sign a <em>lower</em> digit &mdash; say 3 &mdash; would
          need <code class="text-text-primary">H<sup>3</sup>(s)</code>, and
          computing that from
          <code class="text-text-primary">H<sup>5</sup>(s)</code> would
          require running the hash function <em>backwards</em>, which is the
          thing hash functions are specifically designed to make impossible.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          You might spot a gap: an attacker who sees
          <code class="text-text-primary">H<sup>5</sup>(s)</code>
          <em>can</em> hash forward to produce
          <code class="text-text-primary">H<sup>6</sup>(s)</code>,
          <code class="text-text-primary">H<sup>7</sup>(s)</code>, and so on,
          and claim a higher digit. WOTS+ closes this hole with a separate
          <strong class="text-text-primary">checksum chain</strong> whose
          digits move in the <em>opposite</em> direction. Any forward move on
          a message chain forces a backward move on the checksum chain &mdash;
          and forging in both directions at once is infeasible.
        </p>

        <p class="mb-4 text-text-secondary">
          The <strong class="text-text-primary">Winternitz parameter</strong>
          <code class="text-text-primary">w</code> controls the chain length.
          Higher <code class="text-text-primary">w</code> means longer chains,
          fewer chains needed, shorter signatures &mdash; but more hashing.
          Quantroot uses <code class="text-text-primary">w = 256</code>, the
          maximum allowed by FIPS 205.
        </p>
        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          The catch: <strong class="text-text-primary">you can only ever sign
          one message</strong>. If you sign a second message with the same
          WOTS+ key, an attacker sees two intermediate hashes in the same chain
          and can hash either of them forward to forge signatures. WOTS+ is
          <strong class="text-text-primary">one-time by construction</strong>.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 4: Merkle Trees -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-bold">Building Block 2: Merkle Trees</h2>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          Merkle trees are a general-purpose primitive, older than Bitcoin
          itself. They let you commit to many values under a single root hash
          and prove membership of any one value with only
          <code class="text-text-primary">log₂(n)</code> hashes. The next
          building block &mdash; XMSS &mdash; is simply "put WOTS+ keys at the
          leaves of a Merkle tree," so it's worth a brief refresher.
        </p>

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-quantum/20 bg-quantum/5 p-5 mb-6">
          <div class="mb-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-quantum">Mental model</div>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
            Think of a Merkle tree as a <strong class="text-text-primary">family
            tree made of fingerprints</strong>. Each person's fingerprint is
            built by blending the fingerprints of their two children. The
            ancestor at the top of the tree has a single fingerprint that is,
            by construction, a blend of every descendant. Trust the root
            fingerprint and you can verify any single descendant by walking
            back up the tree &mdash; you only need the fingerprints of their
            siblings at each level, not the whole family.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-surface-raised p-6 font-mono text-xs mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          <div class="text-text-secondary text-center">Root = H(H01 ‖ H23)</div>
          <div class="text-text-secondary/50 text-center">/ &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; \</div>
          <div class="text-text-secondary text-center">H01 = H(H0‖H1) &nbsp; &nbsp; H23 = H(H2‖H3)</div>
          <div class="text-text-secondary/50 text-center">/ &nbsp; \ &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; / &nbsp; \</div>
          <div class="text-text-secondary text-center">H0 &nbsp; &nbsp; H1 &nbsp; &nbsp; H2 &nbsp; &nbsp; H3</div>
          <div class="text-text-secondary/50 text-center">| &nbsp; &nbsp; | &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;| &nbsp; &nbsp; |</div>
          <div class="text-text-secondary text-center">v₀ &nbsp; &nbsp; v₁ &nbsp; &nbsp; v₂ &nbsp; &nbsp; v₃</div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          To prove that a specific leaf is in the tree, you provide the
          <strong class="text-text-primary">authentication path</strong>: the
          sibling hashes at each level on the way from the leaf to the root.
          The verifier walks up the path, recomputes the root, and checks it
          matches the published one. A million leaves costs twenty hashes &mdash;
          that logarithmic scaling is why Merkle trees show up in Bitcoin
          blocks, Git objects, and certificate transparency logs.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 5: XMSS -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-bold">Building Block 3: XMSS</h2>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          XMSS &mdash; the eXtended Merkle Signature Scheme &mdash; is exactly
          what the name suggests: a Merkle tree whose leaves are WOTS+ public
          keys. The XMSS public key is just the Merkle root. To sign message
          number <code class="text-text-primary">i</code>, use WOTS+ keypair
          <code class="text-text-primary">i</code> and include the authentication
          path from leaf <code class="text-text-primary">i</code> to the root.
          You've turned one-time signatures into many-time signatures.
        </p>

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-quantum/20 bg-quantum/5 p-5 mb-6">
          <div class="mb-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-quantum">Mental model</div>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
            Picture XMSS as a <strong class="text-text-primary">key ring</strong>
            with many one-use stamps hanging off it. Each stamp has its own
            unique seal (a WOTS+ keypair), and the ring itself has a tiny
            engraved label (the Merkle root) that certifies <em>"all of these
            stamps are mine."</em> To stamp a document, pick an unused stamp,
