        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          Every leaf is still a WOTS+ key, and WOTS+ is still one-time. Which
          brings us to the problem the next section is about.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 6: The State Problem -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-bold">The State Problem</h2>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          XMSS requires the signer to remember which leaves have already been
          used. In practice, that means maintaining a counter: <em>"I've signed
          k messages, the next signature uses leaf k, then increment to k+1."</em>
          That counter is called <strong class="text-text-primary">state</strong>,
          and keeping it correct is suddenly part of the signer's job.
        </p>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          State is <strong class="text-text-primary">poison</strong> for Bitcoin
          wallets. Consider how a Bitcoin private key actually gets used:
        </p>

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-btc-orange/30 bg-btc-orange/5 p-6 mb-6">
          <div class="mb-4 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-btc-orange">Three ways state fails</div>
          <div class="space-y-4 text-sm text-text-secondary">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="mt-0.5 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 rounded-full bg-btc-orange/20 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-btc-orange font-bold">1</span>
              <div><strong class="text-text-primary">Restore from seed.</strong> The mnemonic can regenerate the private key, but it cannot regenerate "which leaves did I already use." Your first post-restore signature might reuse leaf 5 &mdash; the same leaf you used last week. <span class="text-btc-orange">Silent break</span>.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="mt-0.5 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 rounded-full bg-btc-orange/20 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-btc-orange font-bold">2</span>
              <div><strong class="text-text-primary">Two devices, one key.</strong> Laptop and phone both hold the same seed. Both think the next free leaf is 7. Each signs a different transaction with leaf 7. <span class="text-btc-orange">An observer who sees both signatures can forge a third</span>.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="mt-0.5 h-5 w-5 shrink-0 rounded-full bg-btc-orange/20 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-btc-orange font-bold">3</span>
              <div><strong class="text-text-primary">Backup restored.</strong> You restore a backup taken a week ago. The counter rewinds. Every signature you make today reuses a leaf you used since the backup was taken. <span class="text-btc-orange">Undetectable compromise</span>.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          Worst of all, none of these failures are <em>visible</em>. A signature
          made with a reused leaf is structurally valid and every wallet will
          accept it. The compromise only becomes apparent once an attacker
          publishes a forgery &mdash; and by then it's too late. This is why
          "just use XMSS" was never acceptable for Bitcoin.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 7: SPHINCS+ Stateless via PRF -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-bold">SPHINCS+: Stateless via PRF</h2>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          Here's the insight that makes SPHINCS+ work: instead of remembering
          which leaf you've used, <strong class="text-text-primary">derive the
          leaf from the message itself</strong>. SPHINCS+ uses a
          <strong class="text-text-primary">pseudorandom function</strong>
          (PRF) keyed by a secret. A PRF is a function whose output <em>looks</em>
          random to anyone who doesn't know the secret, but is perfectly
          deterministic for anyone who does &mdash; same inputs always produce
          the same output. The same message always maps to the same leaf. No
          counter. No disk. No synchronization between devices.
        </p>

        <!-- Stateful vs stateless comparison -->
        <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2 mb-8">
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-btc-orange/30 bg-surface-raised p-6">
            <div class="mb-4 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-btc-orange">XMSS (Stateful)</div>
            <div class="rounded-lg bg-surface-overlay p-4 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
              <div class="text-text-secondary">counter = <span class="text-btc-orange">load_from_disk()</span></div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary">leaf = counter</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary">sign(message, leaf)</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary">counter += 1</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary"><span class="text-btc-orange">save_to_disk(counter)</span></div>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-text-secondary">
              If the counter is lost, corrupted, or reused across devices,
              security is silently broken.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="rounded-xl border border-quantum/30 bg-surface-raised p-6">
            <div class="mb-4 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-quantum">SPHINCS+ (Stateless)</div>
            <div class="rounded-lg bg-surface-overlay p-4 font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
              <div class="text-text-secondary">leaf = <span class="text-quantum">PRF(secret, message)</span></div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary">sign(message, leaf)</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary"><span class="text-quantum">// no state to save</span></div>
            </div>
            <p class="text-xs text-text-secondary">
              The message deterministically selects the leaf. Same message = same
              leaf = same signature (safe). Different message = different leaf (safe).
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          A deterministic leaf selection has a price: if two different messages
          happen to collide on the same leaf, you get WOTS+-style reuse. To make
          that collision probability astronomically small you need a <em>huge</em>
          number of possible leaves &mdash; Quantroot targets 2<sup>32</sup>,
          roughly four billion. For context, that's more than the total number
          of Bitcoin transactions ever made, several times over. A single XMSS
          tree that large is impractical to compute. The fix is to build the
          tree out of smaller trees.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 8: The Hypertree -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-bold">The Hypertree</h2>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          SPHINCS+ stacks multiple XMSS trees into a
          <strong class="text-text-primary">hypertree</strong> &mdash; a tree of
          trees &mdash; with FORS instances at the very bottom. Each XMSS tree
          is small, so computing its root is cheap. Each layer above 0 is really
          a WOTS+ signature on the root hash of the tree directly below.
        </p>

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-quantum/20 bg-quantum/5 p-5 mb-6">
          <div class="mb-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-quantum">Mental model</div>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
            Think of a hypertree as a <strong class="text-text-primary">nested
            filing cabinet</strong>. The top drawer contains a handful of
            folders, each of which is a smaller cabinet with its own drawers.
            Dig down a few levels and you reach the actual documents. The
            public key on the front of the cabinet is a single label &mdash;
            one short string &mdash; that certifies everything stored inside,
            no matter how deep. You never have to open the whole cabinet to
            prove a single document is in there; you only walk the chain of
            drawers that contain it.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-surface-raised p-6 overflow-hidden">
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <!-- Layer 3 (top) -->
            <div class="flex items-center gap-4">
              <div class="w-20 text-right text-xs text-text-secondary">Layer 3<br/><span class="text-quantum">(top)</span></div>
              <div class="flex-1 flex justify-center">
                <div class="hypertree-layer rounded-lg border border-quantum/30 bg-quantum/5 px-8 py-3 text-center animate-pulse-slow">
                  <div class="text-xs font-mono text-quantum">XMSS Tree</div>
                  <div class="text-[10px] text-text-secondary">Root = Public Key</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-center"><div class="h-6 w-px bg-quantum/30"></div></div>

            <!-- Layer 2 -->
            <div class="flex items-center gap-4">
              <div class="w-20 text-right text-xs text-text-secondary">Layer 2</div>
              <div class="flex-1 flex justify-center gap-4">
                <div class="hypertree-layer rounded-lg border border-quantum/20 bg-quantum/5 px-4 py-2 text-center">
                  <div class="text-xs font-mono text-quantum/70">XMSS</div>
                </div>
                <div class="hypertree-layer rounded-lg border border-quantum/20 bg-quantum/5 px-4 py-2 text-center">
                  <div class="text-xs font-mono text-quantum/70">XMSS</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-center"><div class="h-6 w-px bg-quantum/20"></div></div>

            <!-- Layer 1 -->
            <div class="flex items-center gap-4">
              <div class="w-20 text-right text-xs text-text-secondary">Layer 1</div>
              <div class="flex-1 flex justify-center gap-2">
                <div class="rounded-lg border border-quantum/15 bg-quantum/5 px-3 py-2 text-center">
                  <div class="text-[10px] font-mono text-quantum/60">XMSS</div>
                </div>
                <div class="rounded-lg border border-quantum/15 bg-quantum/5 px-3 py-2 text-center">
                  <div class="text-[10px] font-mono text-quantum/60">XMSS</div>
                </div>
                <div class="rounded-lg border border-quantum/15 bg-quantum/5 px-3 py-2 text-center">
                  <div class="text-[10px] font-mono text-quantum/60">XMSS</div>
                </div>
                <div class="rounded-lg border border-quantum/15 bg-quantum/5 px-3 py-2 text-center">
                  <div class="text-[10px] font-mono text-quantum/60">XMSS</div>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-center"><div class="h-6 w-px bg-quantum/15"></div></div>

            <!-- Layer 0 (bottom XMSS) -->
            <div class="flex items-center gap-4">
              <div class="w-20 text-right text-xs text-text-secondary">Layer 0</div>
              <div class="flex-1 flex justify-center gap-1">
                {Array.from({length: 8}).map(() => (
                  <div class="rounded border border-quantum/10 bg-quantum/5 px-2 py-1">
                    <div class="text-[8px] font-mono text-quantum/50">X</div>
                  </div>
                ))}
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-center"><div class="h-6 w-px bg-btc-orange/30"></div></div>

            <!-- FORS -->
            <div class="flex items-center gap-4">
              <div class="w-20 text-right text-xs text-text-secondary">FORS<br/><span class="text-btc-orange">(bottom)</span></div>
              <div class="flex-1 flex justify-center gap-1">
                {Array.from({length: 10}).map((_, i) => (
                  <div class="rounded border border-btc-orange/20 bg-btc-orange/5 px-2 py-1">
                    <div class="text-[8px] font-mono text-btc-orange/60">T{i}</div>
                  </div>
                ))}
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex justify-center text-xs text-text-secondary mt-2">↑ signs the message</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="mt-6 text-text-secondary">
          A 2<sup>32</sup> leaf capacity is spread across
          <code class="text-text-primary">d=4</code> layers, so no single tree
          is ever bigger than 2<sup>8</sup> = 256 leaves. Signing touches one
          small tree per layer, not one giant tree. The one remaining piece is
          the thing at the very bottom &mdash; the scheme that actually signs
          the message hash.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 9: FORS -->
      <section class="mb-16">
        <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-bold">Building Block 4: FORS</h2>
        <p class="mb-6 text-text-secondary">
          FORS &mdash; Forest Of Random Subsets &mdash; is the signature scheme
          at the bottom of the hypertree. It signs the message hash directly,
          and it is a <strong class="text-text-primary">few-time</strong>
          signature: safe to sign a small number of messages rather than exactly
          one. A FORS key is <code class="text-text-primary">k</code> small
          Merkle trees; to sign a message hash, split it into
          <code class="text-text-primary">k</code> indices, one per tree, and
          reveal one leaf per tree.
        </p>

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-quantum/20 bg-quantum/5 p-5 mb-6">
          <div class="mb-2 text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-quantum">Mental model</div>
          <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">
            Think of FORS as a <strong class="text-text-primary">multi-dial
            combination lock</strong>. A standard lock has one dial and one
            correct number; FORS has <code class="text-text-primary">k</code>
            dials, each drawn from its own set of possible values. To "sign" a
            message, you don't reveal the whole combination &mdash; only the
            specific digit the message points to on each dial, plus enough
            context (an authentication path within each mini-tree) for the
            verifier to check that digit is genuinely part of your lock.
            Different messages light up different dial positions, so each
            signature reveals a different subset of your secrets.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="rounded-xl border border-border bg-surface-raised p-6 font-mono text-xs mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          <div class="grid grid-cols-3 gap-4">
            <div class="text-center">
              <div class="text-quantum mb-1">Tree 0</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary/50">R₀</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary/50">/ \</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary/50">. &nbsp; .</div>
              <div class="text-btc-orange">[★] &nbsp; .</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary/60 text-[10px] mt-1">reveal leaf i₀</div>
            </div>
            <div class="text-center">
              <div class="text-quantum mb-1">Tree 1</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary/50">R₁</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary/50">/ \</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary/50">. &nbsp; .</div>
              <div class="text-btc-orange">. &nbsp; [★]</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary/60 text-[10px] mt-1">reveal leaf i₁</div>
            </div>
            <div class="text-center">
              <div class="text-quantum mb-1">Tree k-1</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary/50">R<sub>k-1</sub></div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary/50">/ \</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary/50">. &nbsp; .</div>
              <div class="text-btc-orange">[★] &nbsp; .</div>
              <div class="text-text-secondary/60 text-[10px] mt-1">reveal leaf i<sub>k-1</sub></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="text-text-secondary">
          SPHINCS+ uses a <strong class="text-text-primary">fresh FORS key per
          signature</strong> &mdash; which is exactly what the hypertree
          provides. Each leaf in the bottom XMSS tree points to its own FORS
          instance, and the PRF makes sure different messages almost always
          land on different leaves. The few-time safety budget resets with
          every signature.
        </p>
      </section>

      <!-- Section 10: Bitcoin's Parameters -->
